## A Century-Old Institution

The **Mages Guild** was founded in 2E 230 by **Vanus Galerion**, a former student of the **Psijics** of Artaeum, with the goal of democratizing access to magical education. For more than a thousand years, the Guild served as a pillar of magical practice throughout the Empire, offering training, regulation, and legitimacy to mages from every province. Its guild halls dotted every major city across **Tamriel**, open to anyone who possessed the talent and the will to learn.

At its height, the Guild was the largest magical organization in history. Its libraries contained millennia of arcane knowledge. Its alchemy laboratories produced potions and enchantments for commerce and war. Its researchers constantly pushed the boundaries of magical understanding. And its rank structure — from simple Associate to supreme Archmage — offered a clear path of advancement for ambitious practitioners.

The **Arcane University** in the **Imperial City** served as headquarters and primary research center. This prestigious institution, located on an island in the middle of Lake Rumare, housed the finest magical minds in the Empire along with the Guild's most precious artifacts. Its Archmage was considered the supreme authority on magical matters throughout the Empire.

## The Question of Necromancy

The debate over **Necromancy** was the worm in the fruit that gnawed at the Guild from within for centuries. The manipulation of the dead raised profound ethical questions that the Guild was never able to resolve satisfactorily. Should this school of magic be banned outright? Tolerated under strict supervision? Encouraged as a legitimate field of research?

Positions varied considerably by province and era. In **Morrowind**, necromancy was traditionally accepted — the **Dunmer** viewed the animation of ancestors as an act of piety. In Cyrodiil, public opinion condemned it, but academics defended academic freedom. In **Skyrim** and **High Rock**, necromancy was regarded with horror and revulsion by the general populace.

Archmage **Hannibal Traven**, who led the Guild during the early fourth century of the Third Era, made the radical decision to ban the practice of necromancy within the Guild entirely. This decision, though applauded by the public, alienated a significant portion of members who considered the ban an arbitrary restriction of academic freedom. Dissenters were expelled, and many joined the ranks of **Mannimarco**.

## Mannimarco and the Order of the Black Worm

**Mannimarco**, the **King of Worms**, had been the sworn enemy of the Mages Guild since its founding. A former classmate of Vanus Galerion at Artaeum, Mannimarco had chosen the path of the darkest necromancy and created the **Order of the Black Worm**, a rival organization dedicated to mastering death and pursuing immortality. His rivalry with the Guild had endured for millennia.

In 3E 433, Mannimarco launched a direct offensive against the Mages Guild. His agents, infiltrated into guild halls across Cyrodiil, began assassinating members, stealing artifacts, and corrupting recruits. The King of Worms sought to destroy the Guild not out of ideology but out of pragmatism: the Guild was the only organized obstacle to his domination of the magical world.

Mannimarco's attack coincided with the **Oblivion Crisis**, doubly weakening the Guild, which had to face two existential threats simultaneously. Resources already stretched thin by the fight against Daedric invasions were stretched further by the necessity of combating the Order of the Black Worm. This dual pressure pushed the Guild to the breaking point.

## The Crisis and Traven's Sacrifice

Archmage **Hannibal Traven** made a desperate decision to combat Mannimarco. Knowing that the King of Worms would use soul magic against anyone who confronted him, Traven chose to sacrifice himself, imprisoning his own soul within a unique **Soul Gem** to entrust to the Champion who would face Mannimarco. This sacrifice would allow the champion to resist the King of Worms' necromantic magic.

Traven's death, though heroic, robbed the Guild of its leader at the worst possible moment. The institution found itself decapitated, without clear leadership or strategic direction. The various guild halls, left to their own devices, adopted contradictory strategies. Some closed their doors; others attempted to negotiate with the Order of the Black Worm; still others continued the fight without coordination.

The Champion of Cyrodiil's victory over Mannimarco eliminated the immediate threat, but the damage was done. The Guild had lost its Archmage, many important members, and much of its public credibility. The image of an organization unable to protect itself against a necromancer — however powerful — undermined public and governmental confidence in the institution.

## The Post-Crisis Dissolution

The years following the Oblivion Crisis saw an accelerated decline of the Mages Guild. The transition into the **Fourth Era**, without an emperor and without the imperial stability that had guaranteed the Guild's functioning, made its maintenance increasingly difficult. Funding dried up, recruits became scarce, and internal divisions deepened.

The official dissolution of the Mages Guild came in the early decades of the Fourth Era. The centuries-old institution fragmented into several rival organizations. In Cyrodiil, the **Synod** and the **College of Whispers** divided the Guild's remains between them, each claiming to be the true heir to Galerion's tradition. Their petty rivalry was a sad contrast to the greatness of the institution they claimed to perpetuate.

In other provinces, responses varied. The **College of Winterhold** in Skyrim maintained its independence, as it always had. In Morrowind, **House Telvanni** absorbed the local mages. In High Rock, private academies replaced the guild halls. Nowhere did any institution manage to reproduce the universality and coherence that the Mages Guild had offered at its peak.

## The Guild's Legacy

The fall of the Mages Guild illustrates a fundamental paradox of institutions: the greater and more powerful they become, the more vulnerable they are to their internal contradictions. The Guild perished not at the hands of an external enemy but because of fractures that centuries had failed to resolve. The necromancy question was merely the most visible symptom of a deeper malaise.

The absence of a unified mages guild in the Fourth Era had profound consequences for magical practice throughout Tamriel. Without centralized regulation, dangerous mages operated unchecked. Without standardized training, the average skill of practitioners declined. Without a network of exchange, discoveries remained isolated. The magical world of the Fourth Era was freer but also more chaotic and more dangerous than that of the Third.

Vanus Galerion's dream — magic that was accessible, regulated, and in service of the common good — did not die entirely with the Guild. But it fragmented into a thousand local initiatives, none possessing the scope or ambition of the original institution. The shadow of what was weighs on every magical practitioner of the Fourth Era, a reminder that there was once a time when mages were united, powerful, and respected.
